        <sect2 id="searching" status="review">
            <title>Searching for Packages</title>
            <para>&appshort; contains an advanced search feature to ensure easy access to
                various packages from the repositories.</para>
            <screenshot>
                <mediaobject>
                    <imageobject>
                        <imagedata fileref="figures/kynaptic-find.png" format="PNG"/>
                    </imageobject>
                    <caption>The search feature</caption>
                </mediaobject>
            </screenshot>
            <para>Below is a description of the first two options available under
                <emphasis>What</emphasis>.</para>
            <variablelist>
                <varlistentry>
                    <term>
                        <guibutton>Dynamic Results</guibutton>
                    </term>
                    <listitem>
                        <para>Checking this box will allow you to do a Dynamic search, where the
                            field below (with the list of all the packages) is automatically
                            filtered while you type. Hence, there is no need to press
                                <guibutton>Find</guibutton> while this option is enabled. </para>
                    </listitem>
                </varlistentry>
                <varlistentry>
                    <term>
                        <guibutton>Regular Expression</guibutton>
                    </term>
                    <listitem>
                        <para>This is a search that utilizes extended regular expressions to search
                            through all the packages available in the repositories. A Regular
                            Expression search can use a number of different Match Operators to
                            unlock more options in searching, ensuring that packages are more
                            accessible. These operators include the standard question mark (?) --
                            used to denote a single unknown characters -- and the wildcard (*),
                            which can be used to denote a plurality of characters.</para>
                    </listitem>
                </varlistentry>
            </variablelist>
            <para>As well as being able to specify the type of search that you wish to perform, you
                can also specify which particular components of the packages you wish to search. All
                the packages in the repositories contain some meta-data; things such as the Name,
                Summary, and the Description of a particular package are all examples of meta-data.
                With &appshort; these three components of the package are all fully searchable
                with the Search engine. You may choose to allow your particular query to search all
                of these fields.</para>
            <para>Once you have found the package in the search results field, you may then perform
                your desired action on the package by <mousebutton>Right</mousebutton> clicking on
                the package and then executing the action which you will wish to later apply.</para>
        </sect2>
